### Culture

Various Air Force personnel pose during the Air Force's 74th birthday celebration at the Pentagon on September 17, 2021.

The culture of the United States Air Force has historically been shaped significantly by its pilots, initially those who flew bombers (influenced by the [Bomber Mafia](/Bomber_Mafia)), and subsequently by fighter pilots ([Fighter Mafia](/Fighter_Mafia)).

In response to a [2007 United States Air Force nuclear weapons incident](/2007_United_States_Air_Force_nuclear_weapons_incident), Secretary of Defense [Robert Gates](/Robert_Gates) accepted the resignations of [Secretary of the Air Force](/United_States_Secretary_of_the_Air_Force) [Michael Wynne](/Michael_Wynne) and [Chief of Staff of the United States Air Force](/Chief_of_Staff_of_the_United_States_Air_Force) [General](/General_(United_States)) [T. Michael Moseley](/T._Michael_Moseley) in June 2009. Moseley's successor, General [Norton A. Schwartz](/Norton_A._Schwartz), a former airlift and special operations pilot, was the first officer appointed to that position without a background as a fighter or bomber pilot. In 2010, *The Washington Post* reported that General Schwartz initiated efforts to dismantle the USAF's rigid class system, particularly within the officer corps.

In 2014, following morale and testing/cheating scandals within the Air Force's [missile launch officer](/Missile_combat_crew) community, Secretary of the Air Force [Deborah Lee James](/Deborah_Lee_James) acknowledged a "systemic problem" in the USAF's management of the nuclear mission.

Daniel L. Magruder Jr. characterizes USAF culture as a synthesis of advanced technology application, individualism, and progressive airpower theory. [Major General](/Major_General) [Charles J. Dunlap Jr.](/Charles_J._Dunlap_Jr.) further posits that the U.S. Air Force's culture includes an [egalitarianism](/Egalitarianism) stemming from officers perceiving themselves as the primary "warriors" of their service, working collaboratively with small groups of enlisted airmen. Historically, Air Force officers have not felt the need for the formal social "distance" from their enlisted force that is customary in other U.S. armed services. While this paradigm is evolving, for much of its existence, the Air Force, unlike its sister services, was an organization where officers primarily engaged in combat, with the enlisted force serving mainly in support roles. When enlisted personnel did face combat situations, such as crew members of multi-crewed aircraft, the close camaraderie forged in shared risk within confined spaces contributed to unique officer/enlisted relationships.

Cultural and career-related issues within the U.S. Air Force have been identified as contributing factors to a shortfall in qualified [UAV](/Unmanned_combat_aerial_vehicle) operators. Despite the significant demand for UAVs to provide continuous surveillance for American troops during the Iraq War, the USAF did not establish a dedicated career field for piloting them until the final year of that conflict. In 2014, the USAF revised its RPA training syllabus again, following substantial aircraft losses during training and in response to a critical GAO report on drone program management. Paul Scharre has observed that cultural differences between the USAF and the U.S. Army have hindered the adoption of each service's drone handling innovations by the other.

Many of the U.S. Air Force's formal and informal traditions are a blend of those inherited from the [Royal Air Force](/Royal_Air_Force) (such as dining-ins/mess nights) and the experiences of its predecessor organizations, including the [U.S. Army Air Service](/U.S._Army_Air_Service), [U.S. Army Air Corps](/U.S._Army_Air_Corps), and the [U.S. Army Air Forces](/U.S._Army_Air_Forces). These traditions range from "Friday Name Tags" in flying units to an annual "Mustache Month." The practice of using ["challenge coins"](/Challenge_coin) dates back to World War I, when a member of an aero squadron purchased medallions bearing his unit's emblem for the entire squadron. Another unique Air Force tradition is the "[roof stomp](/Roof_stomp)," performed by Airmen to welcome a new commander or commemorate events such as retirements.

### Organization

The administrative structure of the U.S. Air Force places it within the [Department of the Air Force](/United_States_Department_of_the_Air_Force), one of the three military departments under the [Department of Defense](/United_States_Department_of_Defense). This department is overseen by the civilian [Secretary of the Air Force](/United_States_Secretary_of_the_Air_Force), operating under the authority, direction, and control of the [Secretary of Defense](/United_States_Secretary_of_Defense). The senior leadership within the [Office of the Secretary](/Office_of_the_Secretary_of_the_Air_Force) includes the [Under Secretary of the Air Force](/United_States_Under_Secretary_of_the_Air_Force), four [Assistant Secretaries of the Air Force](/Assistant_Secretary_of_the_Air_Force), and the [General Counsel](/General_Counsel_of_the_Department_of_the_Air_Force), all appointed by the president with the [advice and consent](/Advice_and_consent) of the [Senate](/United_States_Senate). The senior uniformed leadership within the [Air Staff](/Air_Staff_(United_States)) comprises the [Chief of Staff of the Air Force](/Chief_of_Staff_of_the_United_States_Air_Force) and the [Vice Chief of Staff of the United States Air Force](/Vice_Chief_of_Staff_of_the_United_States_Air_Force).

The directly subordinate commands and units are categorized as [Field Operating Agencies](/List_of_United_States_Air_Force_Field_Operating_Agencies) (FOA) and [Direct Reporting Units](/Direct_Reporting_Unit) (DRU), with a currently unused category of Separate Operating Agency. The [Major Command](/List_of_Major_Commands_of_the_United_States_Air_Force) (MAJCOM) represents the highest hierarchical level of command. As of September 30, 2006, the USAF included ten major commands, including the [Air Force Reserve Command](/Air_Force_Reserve_Command). The [Numbered Air Force](/List_of_Numbered_Air_Forces_of_the_United_States_Air_Force) (NAF) serves as a command level directly beneath the MAJCOM, followed by Operational Command (now unused), [Air Division](/USAF_Air_Division) (also now unused), [Wing](/List_of_Wings_of_the_United_States_Air_Force), [Group](/List_of_United_States_Air_Force_Groups), [Squadron](/List_of_United_States_Air_Force_squadrons), and Flight.

